title: #66 Japón emite un aviso sobre un posible megaterremoto de Nankai Trough después del temblor de magnitud 7,1 (inglés)
text:
Portada
mis comunidades
otras secciones
[#5](c5#c-5) Mi hijo se casó allí el viernes. A la mujer le cogió de lleno el anterior que trabaja en el sur.
Cruzaremos los dedos.
[#17](c17#c-17) Eso es que los tacos han cogido holgura y ya no se fijan bien. Hay que poner tacos nuevos más gordos o rellenar con el aquaplast/mortero/silicona (salvo americanos que con una hoja de papel les vale) La próxima vez te llevas unos más gordos y se cambian en un decir haiku
Fuera coñas, espero que estén bien que Japón es bastante movidito! Por lo menos la gente y los edificios están bien diseñados/entrenados con lo que suelen apañarse bastante bien.
[#10](c10#c-10) Aunque la altura de 30 metros así a bote pronto parece una locura, los barcos comerciales se construyen para aguantar ondas de 50 metros.
El problema del tsunami no es tanto la altura, como la masa de agua que arrastra, una onda de 10 metros de alto y 100 de largo es devastadora.
[#58](c58#c-58) Si, pero 30 metros de altura en un tsunami como dices lleva una gran masa de agua, y dada esa altura puede penetrar muy adentro de la costa, no solo matando a gente que podria sentirse a salvo sino destuyendo la industria y la agricultura en muchos kilometros cuadrados
[#59](c59#c-59) Creo que no me he explicado bien, 30 metros puede ser menos destructivo que 10 metros, lo que importa es la masa de agua asociada al tsunami.
Esta claro que como tú dices, que si es tres veces más grande, no solo en altura, pues será catastrófica.
[#2](c2#c-2) Aquí otro enlace, esta vez en caribeño y con algunos vídeos.
https://www.elcaribe.com.do/panorama/internacionales/videos-terremoto-en-japon-genera-alerta-inedito-en-el-pais-y-que-asusta/
[#56](c56#c-56) No entiendo porque el artículo señala que el último desastre de este tipo fue hace 70 años cuando el terremoto y tsunami de 2011 fue con una magnitud de 8'9 y con olas que en algunas zonas superaron los 30 metros de altura.
Teniendo en cuenta que son unas islas con mas bien pocos recursos naturales ... ¿no les saldría a cuenta, no se, emigrar a Cuenca, Teruel , León...?
Si echan de menos el malvivir , pueden pasar las vacaciones en Murcia.
No se vosotros, pero entre turistas británicos y colonos japoneses , tengo claro lo que prefiero.
[#13](c13#c-13) Yo cambiaba los guiris de baleares por los japoneses para que no se estresen y ya de paso tenemos un turismo mucho más tranquilo...
[#25](c25#c-25) Igual para aclimatarlos ,según van llegando que pasen primero por las islas, pero la idea es alejarlos de la costa tanto como se pueda. Que es acercar a un japones al mar y empiezan a pasar cosas...
[#26](c26#c-26) Pues murcia... casi que mejor tenerlos en madrid y alrededores entonces pero por lo menos son turistas tranquilitos.
[#7](c7#c-7) ¿Da tiempo a desmantelar las centrales nucleares de japón? Yo no sé en qué piensa la gente para vivir en sitios donde los terremotos de más de 7, tsunamis, huracanes, inundaciones, heladas, sequías y todo lo demás son frecuentes, son como lugares inhóspitos. Deberían estar deshabitados. Ni mucho menos tener centrales nucleares en esos lugares.
[#22](c22#c-22) y anda que el que tuvo la "genial" idea de central TODA la industria mundial de semiconductores en un paissssito amenazado permanentemente de invasión por su primo el de Zumosol de enfrente (Taiwán) y como respaldo otro paisssito permanentemente amenazado por su hermanito peleón del Norte (Corea del Sur), unos geniussss de narices oye...
Lo de la bolsa del otro día era absolutamente irrelevante y no pasó nada. Excepto en menéame, por supuesto.

author: Moneywise
title: Want To Be a Millionaire? Embrace These 13 Habits Now
text:
GOBankingRates Want To Be a Millionaire? Embrace These 13 Habits Now Read full article John Csiszar 29 December 2023 at 1:00 am · 6-min read shapecharge / iStock/Getty Images
One million dollars is a number that many people set as a target for their retirement nest egg , and it has something of a mythical feel about it. The very idea of being a millionaire symbolizes great wealth for most Americans, and indeed only about 8.8% of Americans actually are millionaires, putting them in the category of the financial elite.
Experts: Make These 7 Money Resolutions If You Want To Become Rich on an Average Salary
Learn: 3 Things You Must Do When Your Savings Reach $50,000
However, there are concrete steps that anyone can take to increase their chances of reaching a seven-digit net worth. By starting early enough and implementing some of these financial steps, you may find yourself in this rarefied company more easily than you think .
Sponsored: Get Paid To Scroll. Start Now
Start Investing Early Probably the single biggest step you can take towards achieving millionaire status is to start investing early. As Mark Cuban said, “When investing, the best thing you can do is start early.” Socking away as little as $200 per month when you are 20 can translate to over $1 million by age 65 if you earn an 8% return on your investments. While no investment return is guaranteed, the long-term average return of the S&P 500 index easily eclipses this 8% target. However, as billionaire Warren Buffet advised: “The best time to plant a tree was 20 years ago. The second-best time is now.” So, better to start now than not at all.
Save Until It Hurts You might have heard that you should save at least 10% of your income to generate long-term wealth. While that’s a great start, if you want to become a millionaire , you’ll have to save until it hurts. This means different things for different people. If you’re only earning $25,000 per year, saving 10% of your money might hurt a little — but try pushing it to 15% or 20%. If you earn $200,000 per year, you might be able to push that savings rate to 50% or more. Or, to put it simply, listen to Buffet: “Do not save what is left after spending; spend what is left after saving.”
Story continues I’m a Financial Advisor: Here’s the No. 1 Piece of Advice I Would Give My Younger Self
Invest in Appreciating Assets, Not Depreciating Ones One of the most important steps in reaching millionaire status is to only put your money into investments that will generate a positive return for you. In plain English, this means you should be investing in assets that have demonstrated long-term earnings potential, like the stock market and real estate, not in assets that lose value every day, like new cars or consumer goods.
Continually Increase Your Income The cost of living goes up nearly every year, so if your income doesn’t grow as well, you’ll never generate true wealth. Regularly ask for raises at your job so your income rises faster than the inflation rate. If you can’t squeeze any more money out of your current job, consider taking on a side gig or some type of additional work so you can continue to raise your income.
Generate Passive Income Millionaires and billionaires agree: Passive income is incredibly important to amassing a fortune. As Buffet said, “If you don’t find a way to make money while you sleep, you will work until you die,” It’s hard to get wealthy just from earning a salary. But you can get to millionaire status a lot more quickly if you generate income that you don’t have to work for, known as passive income. A classic example is rental income. Once you buy a rental property, you’ll get paid every month by your renters without having to do any additional work beyond routine maintenance and repairs. If your rental income exceeds the amount you pay for your mortgage, property tax and other costs, you’re essentially using other people’s money to pay for your property while you sit and watch its value increase. Be like investor and author Robert Kiyosaki, who said, “my passive income exceeds my expenses. That’s financial independence.”
Pay Off Credit Card Debt Knocking down your credit card balances won’t earn you any money, but it might still be the best “investment” you ever make. If you carry a balance on your credit card, you may be paying interest of 20% or more annually. No investment you make can reliably generate those types of returns, so paying off any outstanding balances you have is one of the best possible uses of your money.
Maximize Your 401(k) Match If you’re lucky enough to have a 401(k) match at your job, you absolutely must take advantage of it each and every year. A 401(k) match may be the closest thing to free money you’ll ever receive, and best of all, it’s deposited into a tax-advantaged investment account. Even if you can’t contribute the absolute maximum to your 401(k) every year, at least contribute enough to claim your full employer match.
Maintain a Top-Tier Credit Score As financial guru Suze Orman said, “A good credit score is better than money.” A top-tier credit score won’t put any money in your pocket directly, but it can save you literally tens of thousands of dollars over your lifetime, perhaps even more. With a credit score above 740, you can usually qualify for the lowest available interest rates on everything from home mortgages to auto loans, and the savings can really pile up. A $300,000, 30-year mortgage at 3.0% vs. 4.5%, for example, will save you over $74,000 in interest over the life of the loan.
Live in an Affordable Community America is a vast country with plenty of comfortable places to live. If you can live in a lower-cost area while still earning the same salary, it’s the same as if you got a significant raise. As more and more companies are allowing their employees to work remotely, see if you can move to a less-expensive area and boost your savings rate to help you achieve millionaire status.
Be Entrepreneurial and Take Calculated Risks “The only limit to our realization of tomorrow will be our doubts of today,” said U.S. President Franklin D. Roosevelt. Millionaires are often willing to take smart risks to grow their money through new business ventures. Calculated risks and entrepreneurship can lead to greater reward.
Network and Seek Mentorship Surrounding yourself with knowledgeable peers and mentors accelerates learning and unlocks opportunities. As Shark Tank’s Daymond John said,”Finding mentors has been key to my success.” Millionaires invest time in networking and mentor relationships.
Learn Constantly and Improve Your Skills “Risk comes from not knowing what you’re doing,” said Buffett. Education and skill development are lifelong pursuits. Millionaires continually learn to expand their knowledge, abilities and opportunities.
Practice Intentional Goal Setting Millionaires set clear goals for their money and review them regularly. Intentional goal setting and tracking progress are keys to success. “Decide what you want, decide what you are willing to exchange for it. Establish your priorities and go to work,” said American tycoon H. L. Hunt.
Laura Beck contributed to the reporting for this article.
